@article{ISI:000339494600009,
 abstract = {The design of new molecular scaffolds for the selective recognition or
transport of anions is often critical, because subtle changes in the
substitution pattern may drastically impact the targeted properties.
Herein, detailed spectroscopic and X-ray crystal-structure analyses were
used to investigate the effect of the substitution pattern of a new
series of N2O2 or N-4 anion sensors. Our study evidences two distinct
in-in and in-out conformations depending on the nature of the
substituent (e. g., phenol vs. aniline). Interestingly, because of
intramolecular hydrogen bonds involving the -OH or the -NH2 functions,
the dipyrrin subunit only acts as a scaffold and does not participate in
the anion binding. Furthermore, the nature of the meso substituent was
not critical, as similar binding affinities were measured for meso-C6H5
or meso-C6F5 ligands. Hence, the meso position can be further modified
without any noticeable changes to the electron density on the
dipyrromethene subunit.},
